[03:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Here\'s the trap almost everyone falls into today. A system that changes itself with no way to tell if it\'s actually getting better is just a system that drifts. You need a scoreboard. That'

[03:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'scoreboard is evals, and an eval is dead simple. It\'s a set of pass-fail checks for a task you care about. If Claude writes your commit messages,'

[03:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'your eval is five example diffs, and the message a great engineer would write for each one. Now, you have ground truth. Before any change, Claude runs the evals and scores itself.'

[04:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'After the change, it runs them again. Number went up, keep it. Number went down, throw it away. And you can even automate that scoreboard with a hook. Claude code can fire a command the moment it finishes a task,'

[04:21] [scene:talk]
